dispute resolution.As he discusses Supreme Court decisions dealing with unions and labor in a variety of different areas, Getman offers an interesting historical perspective to illuminate the ways in which the Court has been an influence in the failures of the labor movement. During more than sixty years that have seen the Supreme Court take a dominant role, both unions and the institution of collective bargaining have been substantially weakened. While it is difficult to measure the extent of the Court’s responsibility for the current weak state of organized labor and many other factors have, of course, contributed, it seems clear to Getman that the Supreme Court has played an important role in transforming the law and defeating policies that support the labor movement.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aLabor laws and legislationzUnited StatesxCases. 0aLabor laws and legislationzUnited StatesxInterpretation and construction. 0aLabor unionsxCasesxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aLabor unionsxLaw and legislationzUnited StatesxCases. 4aLabor History. 4aLegal History & Studies. 4aU.S. History. 7aLAW / Labor & Employment.2bisacsh  aLabor unions, Supreme Court, labor law, labor relations, dispute resolution, labor movement.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749340uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170365240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501703652423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501703652/original  a978-3-11-066749-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles